    <section class="section-block faq-section">
      <div class="container">
        <p class="label">[ FREQUENTLY ASKED QUESTIONS ]</p>
        <h2 >FAQ</h2>
        <div class="faq-chat">

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q-btn" type="button">
              <span>Is HODL the same as &ldquo;hold&rdquo;?</span>
              <span class="faq-arrow">&rsaquo;</span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-bubble-wrap">
              <div class="faq-bubble" data-text="HODL originated as a misspelling of &quot;hold&quot; in a 2013 BitcoinTalk forum post. While it functionally means the same thing &mdash; holding your crypto instead of selling &mdash; it has taken on a deeper cultural significance as a statement of conviction and long-term commitment. Some retroactively interpret it as an acronym for &quot;Hold On for Dear Life,&quot; but the original was simply a typo that became a movement."></div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q-btn" type="button">
              <span>How long should you HODL?</span>
              <span class="faq-arrow">&rsaquo;</span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-bubble-wrap">
              <div class="faq-bubble" data-text="There is no universal answer. Most HODLers think in terms of at least one full market cycle (roughly 4 years for Bitcoin, aligned with halving events). Many committed holders plan in decades. The right holding period depends on your financial goals, conviction in the asset, and personal circumstances. The key principle is that you should not be holding with a short-term exit in mind &mdash; if you need the money within months, HODLing is not the right strategy."></div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q-btn" type="button">
              <span>Should you HODL altcoins or only Bitcoin?</span>
              <span class="faq-arrow">&rsaquo;</span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-bubble-wrap">
              <div class="faq-bubble" data-text="Bitcoin has the strongest HODL thesis due to its absolute scarcity (21 million cap), longest track record, largest network effect, and most decentralized governance. Most altcoins do not survive full market cycles &mdash; many lose 90%+ of their value and never recover. If you HODL altcoins, apply significantly more scrutiny: evaluate the team, technology, tokenomics, competition, and real-world adoption. The bar for holding an altcoin for years should be much higher than for Bitcoin."></div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q-btn" type="button">
              <span>What if the price drops 80%?</span>
              <span class="faq-arrow">&rsaquo;</span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-bubble-wrap">
              <div class="faq-bubble" data-text="An 80% drawdown has happened multiple times in Bitcoin's history, and each time the price eventually recovered to set new all-time highs. However, past recovery does not guarantee future recovery. The correct response to an 80% drop depends on whether your original investment thesis still holds. If the fundamentals have not changed, many HODLers view deep drawdowns as accumulation opportunities (buying more at lower prices). If fundamentals have deteriorated, a reassessment is warranted. The critical factor is that you should never be in a position where an 80% drop forces you to sell."></div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q-btn" type="button">
              <span>Is DCA better than buying all at once?</span>
              <span class="faq-arrow">&rsaquo;</span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-bubble-wrap">
              <div class="faq-bubble" data-text="Mathematically, lump-sum investing outperforms DCA about two-thirds of the time in upward-trending markets. However, DCA dramatically reduces the risk of catastrophic timing &mdash; investing everything right before a major crash. In crypto, where 50%+ drawdowns are common, DCA provides meaningful psychological and financial protection. For most people, DCA is the better approach because it removes emotion, automates discipline, and spreads risk across time. The best strategy is often the one you can actually stick with through a full cycle."></div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q-btn" type="button">
              <span>When is it okay to sell?</span>
              <span class="faq-arrow">&rsaquo;</span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-bubble-wrap">
              <div class="faq-bubble" data-text="HODL does not mean &quot;never sell.&quot; Rational reasons to sell include: reaching a predefined financial goal (buying a house, retiring, funding education), the fundamental investment thesis changing (protocol compromise, regulatory existential threat), portfolio rebalancing to manage concentration risk, or life circumstances requiring liquidity. The key is that selling should be a planned, rational decision &mdash; not an emotional reaction to a price drop or a fear-driven panic exit. Write your exit criteria in advance, and follow them when triggered."></div>
            </div>
          </div>

        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

